C^{'}(x)=-\frac{\pi}{180}S(x)
 \begin{align} \frac{d}{dx}S(x)&=\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{S(x+h)-S(x)}{h}&\\     &     = \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\sin(\frac{2\pi}{360}(x+h))-\sin(\frac{2\pi}{360}x)}{h} &\text{from measure to measure relation}\\ &=\frac{\pi}{180}\cos{\frac{\pi}{180}}=\frac{\pi}{180}C(x).& \text{from classic derivative formula}  \end{align}  
